As well as occupying pits and crevices,
E. tuberculata
is found submerged in warm, saline pools in the littoral fringe ( Kristensen 1965 ; Vermeij 1973b ; Bandel & Wedler 1987 ;
Lang et al . 1998
). This may account for its salinity tolerance of 34–40 ppt, which is higher than that of other sympatric littorinids (
Flores 1973b
). Bandel (1974a) observed that juveniles crawled out of pools that were diluted by rain, whereas
Lang et al . (1998)
found snails in pools with nearly fresh water as well as in hypersaline pools, and suggested that this was for the purpose of rehydration. Coomans (1962) observed that animals died in less than a week if kept submerged in seawater, whereas Yipp & Carefoot (1988) reported survival for more than two weeks. Survival is greater in air, up to 32 days ( Yipp & Carefoot 1988 ; Britton 1992 ) or even 12 months ( Mattox 1949 ; although there may have been confusion with the more resistant
Tectarius antonii , Abbott 1954b
).
